{"title_page": "Don Julio", "text_new": "{{short des(A WHITE PERSON OWNS THIS TEQUILA AND IT PISSES ME OFF !!!produced in Mexico}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox beverage\n|name=Don Julio\n|image=Don Julio 2014.jpg\n|image_size=220\n|type=Premium [[tequila]]\n|manufacturer= [[Diageo Brands]]\n|origin= [[Mexico]]\n|introduced= 1942\n|discontinued=\n|proof= 80\n|related=\n|variants= Blanco, Reposado, A\u00f1ejo, 1942, Real, 70\n}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Tequila Don Julio, S.A. de C.V.\n| logo = \n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation = [[Atotonilco El Alto]], [[Jalisco, Mexico]] (1942)\n| key_people = Don Julio Gonzalez Estrada, founder\n| industry = [[Distilled beverages]]\n| products = [[Tequila]] \n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.donjulio.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Don Julio''' is a brand of [[tequila]] produced in [[Mexico]]. It is the largest brand in value and eighth largest in volume.<ref>(Source: Nielsen e ISCAM, february 2017)</ref> It is distilled, manufactured, bottled, sold, and distributed by Tequila Don Julio, S.A. de C.V. from its corporate facility in the Colonia El Chichimeco district, in the city of [[Atotonilco El Alto]], [[Jalisco, Mexico]].<ref>[http://www.tequilasource.com/donjuliotequila.htm ''Don Julio Tequila: Made in the Same Way Since 1942 .''] Retrieved November 27, 2009.</ref>  It is distributed in the United States by [[Diageo]], under licensing from its patent holder, Tequila Don Julio, ''Sociedad An\u00f3nima de Capital Variable'', Jalisco, Mexico,<ref>[http://www.tequilasource.com/donjuliotequila.htm Distributed in the U.S. by the Diageo company]</ref> but it is sold worldwide.<ref>[http://www.tequilasource.com/donjuliotequila.htm Diageo distributor]</ref>\n\n==History==\nDon Julio Tequila is named after its founder, Don Julio Gonz\u00e1lez-Frausto Estrada, who began distilling tequila in 1942 at age 17.<ref>{{cite news |title=Don Julio: 60 anos de hacer tequila. |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-4959165_ITM |work=[[Mural (Guadalajara)|Mural]] |date=6 December 2002 |accessdate=2008-10-24 | first=Angel | last=Rivas}}</ref> Acknowledging the benefits of [[vertical integration]], Gonzalez-Frausto established his own distillery, La Primavera, and spent the next 40 years improving his craft. He experimented with controlling various aspects of the tequila-making process, \"from the cultivation of the agave to the bottling of the final product.\" He named his distillery ''La Primavera'' (the Springtime) where he produced his first brand Tres Magueyes. He is said to have \"spent nearly forty years perfecting the craft.\"<ref name=\"Don Julio the founder\">[http://www.donjulio.com/en-row/theman.htm Don Julio the founder] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121091447/http://www.donjulio.com/en-row/theman.htm |date=21 November 2008 }}</ref> Don Julio's first tequilas were shared with friends only, but as word on the quality of his tequila spread, he officially founded a company to put him in business.<ref name=\"Don Julio the founder\"/> In 1983, [[Marco Cedano]] returned to Don Julio to work as an engineer, where he served as Master Distiller and Distillery Manager of Tequila.<ref name=Book2>{{cite book|last1=Emmons|first1=Bob|title=The Book of Tequila : A Complete Guide|url=https://archive.org/details/bookoftequilacom00emmo|url-access=registration|date=1997|publisher=Open Court|location=Chicago|isbn=978-0812693515|page=x}}</ref> In 1985 Don Julio Gonz\u00e1lez-Frausto celebrated his 60th Birthday, his sons commemorated the date by creating a Tequila in his name, Don Julio. Following the sheer popularity of the tequila in Guadalajara and neighboring cities they decided to launch the tequila.\n\nIn 1999 the now defunct, The [[Seagram Company Ltd.]], had invested in Tequila Don Julio, S.A. de C.V. of Mexico. The expanded agave plantations were a joint venture between the Gonzalez-Frausto, Funtanet, Andrade Rivera Torres, and Cuaik families. In 1999 Don Julio Gonzalez, delighted to forge a relationship with Seagram, stated, \"I am proud that the Gonzalez-Frausto family joins with the Seagram family in a global effort behind Don Julio Tequila. I am committed to overseeing personally the agave plantations that are so vital to the superior and unique quality of the Tequila that bears my name.\" Diageo signed a joint venture in with Casa Cuervo in 2003, selling a 50 per cent stake in Don Julio for $100 million.<ref>[http://seekingalpha.com/article/259338-diageo-may-seek-to-acquire-jose-cuervo SeekingAlpha.com]</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Diageo agreed to a deal to take full control of the Don Julio brand. In exchange, [[Jose Cuervo]] will receive the [[Old Bushmills Distillery]] and pay Diageo $408m.<ref>{{cite news | last = McLoughlin | first = Gavin | title = Diageo sells off Bushmills to drinks giant Jose Cuervo | newspaper = [[Irish Independent]] | date = 2014-11-04 | url = http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/diageo-sells-off-bushmills-to-drinks-giant-jose-cuervo-30714656.html | accessdate = 2014-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==Founder==\nDon Julio Gonzalez-Frausto Estrada was born on the 7th of January 1925 in Atotonilco, Jalisco, where today's main facility is located. Don Julio learned the meaning of responsibility at an early age by working at his uncle Jos\u00e9's tequila distillery. At the age of 23 he married Dorothea Garcia with whom he had 9 children. In 1942 he started a tequila distillery which would later be known as \"La Primavera.\" By 1951, with the brand Tres Magueyes, he was on a path that would later become Tequila Don Julio in its different variants: Blanco, Reposado, A\u00f1ejo, 70, 1942 and Real. Don Julio Gonz\u00e1lez-Frausto Estrada died on Tuesday, March 20, 2012 from natural causes.<ref name=\"Julio Death\">{{cite news|last=Lapcewich|first=Maggie|title=Don Julio Gonz\u00e1lez Estrada, Tequila Pioneer Dies at the Age of 87|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20120321006740/en/Don-Julio-Gonz\u00e1lez-Estrada-Tequila-Pioneer-Dies#.UwZSGihBCfS|accessdate=20 February 2014|newspaper=Business Wire|date=21 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Process==\n\nThe agave for Don Julio's Tequila is grown in the highland area of Atotonilco on the family estate. Tequila's major aging process over time takes place in conjunction with the development of agave plants, given that they take seven years to reach maturity. Every agave plant is harvested by hand. The agave plant is cut from its roots and then the spearlike leaves are sheered off. The core that is left is called a pi\u00f1a, which is the raw material used for the making of tequila. The pi\u00f1as are transported on a truck to Don Julio's Distillery where they are cut into equal sized pieces so that they bake evenly. The pi\u00f1as are loaded into brick ovens where they are slowly baked over the course of several days. Then the baked pi\u00f1as are crushed and doused with water, which releases the sweet agave syrup called agave juice. Then yeast is added to the agave water and is left to ferment. After the fermentation process is complete it results in a sweet, slight alcoholic agave beer which is then put into stills where it is distilled to become tequila. At last it is put into stainless steel tanks before bottling, or ex-bourbon casks for aging.<ref name=\"Tequila making\">{{cite web|last=Kleinman|first=Geoff|title=How Tequila is Made: Behind the Scenes of Don Julio Tequila|url=http://www.drinkspirits.com/tequila/tequila-made-scenes-don-julio-tequila/|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Varieties==\n\n* Don Julio Blanco (available also in the US)\n* Don Julio Reposado (available also in the US)<ref>[http://www.tequilasource.com/donjuliotequila.htm ''Don Julio Tequila: Made in the same way since 1942 .''] Retrieved November 27, 2009.</ref>\n* Don Julio A\u00f1ejo (available also in the US)\n* Don Julio 70 A\u00f1ejo Claro (available also in the US)\n* Don Julio 1942 A\u00f1ejo (available also in the US)\n* Don Julio Real Extra A\u00f1ejo (available also in the US)\n\nSeveral of these offerings have performed well at international [[spirit ratings]] competitions.  For example, Don Julio's Real tequila was awarded double gold medals at the 2008 and 2011 San Francisco World Spirits Competition and a silver medal at the 2012 competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proof66.com/tequila/don-julio-real-tequila.html|title=Proof66.com Ratings Summary for Don Julio Real|publisher= |date= |accessdate=2012-10-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.donjulio.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Diageo plc}}\n\n[[Category:Tequila]]\n[[Category:Diageo brands]]\n[[Category:Alcoholic drink brands]]\n[[Category:Mexican brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brand of tequila produced in Mexico}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox beverage\n|name=Don Julio\n|image=Don Julio 2014.jpg\n|image_size=220\n|type=Premium [[tequila]]\n|manufacturer= [[Diageo Brands]]\n|origin= [[Mexico]]\n|introduced= 1942\n|discontinued=\n|proof= 80\n|related=\n|variants= Blanco, Reposado, A\u00f1ejo, 1942, Real, 70\n}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Tequila Don Julio, S.A. de C.V.\n| logo = \n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation = [[Atotonilco El Alto]], [[Jalisco, Mexico]] (1942)\n| key_people = Don Julio Gonzalez Estrada, founder\n| industry = [[Distilled beverages]]\n| products = [[Tequila]] \n| homepage = {{URL|http://www.donjulio.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Don Julio''' is a brand of [[tequila]] produced in [[Mexico]]. It is the largest brand in value and eighth largest in volume.<ref>(Source: Nielsen e ISCAM, february 2017)</ref> It is distilled, manufactured, bottled, sold, and distributed by Tequila Don Julio, S.A. de C.V. from its corporate facility in the Colonia El Chichimeco district, in the city of [[Atotonilco El Alto]], [[Jalisco, Mexico]].<ref>[http://www.tequilasource.com/donjuliotequila.htm ''Don Julio Tequila: Made in the Same Way Since 1942 .''] Retrieved November 27, 2009.</ref>  It is distributed in the United States by [[Diageo]], under licensing from its patent holder, Tequila Don Julio, ''Sociedad An\u00f3nima de Capital Variable'', Jalisco, Mexico,<ref>[http://www.tequilasource.com/donjuliotequila.htm Distributed in the U.S. by the Diageo company]</ref> but it is sold worldwide.<ref>[http://www.tequilasource.com/donjuliotequila.htm Diageo distributor]</ref>\n\n==History==\nDon Julio Tequila is named after its founder, Don Julio Gonz\u00e1lez-Frausto Estrada, who began distilling tequila in 1942 at age 17.<ref>{{cite news |title=Don Julio: 60 anos de hacer tequila. |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-4959165_ITM |work=[[Mural (Guadalajara)|Mural]] |date=6 December 2002 |accessdate=2008-10-24 | first=Angel | last=Rivas}}</ref> Acknowledging the benefits of [[vertical integration]], Gonzalez-Frausto established his own distillery, La Primavera, and spent the next 40 years improving his craft. He experimented with controlling various aspects of the tequila-making process, \"from the cultivation of the agave to the bottling of the final product.\" He named his distillery ''La Primavera'' (the Springtime) where he produced his first brand Tres Magueyes. He is said to have \"spent nearly forty years perfecting the craft.\"<ref name=\"Don Julio the founder\">[http://www.donjulio.com/en-row/theman.htm Don Julio the founder] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121091447/http://www.donjulio.com/en-row/theman.htm |date=21 November 2008 }}</ref> Don Julio's first tequilas were shared with friends only, but as word on the quality of his tequila spread, he officially founded a company to put him in business.<ref name=\"Don Julio the founder\"/> In 1983, [[Marco Cedano]] returned to Don Julio to work as an engineer, where he served as Master Distiller and Distillery Manager of Tequila.<ref name=Book2>{{cite book|last1=Emmons|first1=Bob|title=The Book of Tequila : A Complete Guide|url=https://archive.org/details/bookoftequilacom00emmo|url-access=registration|date=1997|publisher=Open Court|location=Chicago|isbn=978-0812693515|page=x}}</ref> In 1985 Don Julio Gonz\u00e1lez-Frausto celebrated his 60th Birthday, his sons commemorated the date by creating a Tequila in his name, Don Julio. Following the sheer popularity of the tequila in Guadalajara and neighboring cities they decided to launch the tequila.\n\nIn 1999 the now defunct, The [[Seagram Company Ltd.]], had invested in Tequila Don Julio, S.A. de C.V. of Mexico. The expanded agave plantations were a joint venture between the Gonzalez-Frausto, Funtanet, Andrade Rivera Torres, and Cuaik families. In 1999 Don Julio Gonzalez, delighted to forge a relationship with Seagram, stated, \"I am proud that the Gonzalez-Frausto family joins with the Seagram family in a global effort behind Don Julio Tequila. I am committed to overseeing personally the agave plantations that are so vital to the superior and unique quality of the Tequila that bears my name.\" Diageo signed a joint venture in with Casa Cuervo in 2003, selling a 50 per cent stake in Don Julio for $100 million.<ref>[http://seekingalpha.com/article/259338-diageo-may-seek-to-acquire-jose-cuervo SeekingAlpha.com]</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Diageo agreed to a deal to take full control of the Don Julio brand. In exchange, [[Jose Cuervo]] will receive the [[Old Bushmills Distillery]] and pay Diageo $408m.<ref>{{cite news | last = McLoughlin | first = Gavin | title = Diageo sells off Bushmills to drinks giant Jose Cuervo | newspaper = [[Irish Independent]] | date = 2014-11-04 | url = http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/diageo-sells-off-bushmills-to-drinks-giant-jose-cuervo-30714656.html | accessdate = 2014-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==Founder==\nDon Julio Gonzalez-Frausto Estrada was born on the 7th of January 1925 in Atotonilco, Jalisco, where today's main facility is located. Don Julio learned the meaning of responsibility at an early age by working at his uncle Jos\u00e9's tequila distillery. At the age of 23 he married Dorothea Garcia with whom he had 9 children. In 1942 he started a tequila distillery which would later be known as \"La Primavera.\" By 1951, with the brand Tres Magueyes, he was on a path that would later become Tequila Don Julio in its different variants: Blanco, Reposado, A\u00f1ejo, 70, 1942 and Real. Don Julio Gonz\u00e1lez-Frausto Estrada died on Tuesday, March 20, 2012 from natural causes.<ref name=\"Julio Death\">{{cite news|last=Lapcewich|first=Maggie|title=Don Julio Gonz\u00e1lez Estrada, Tequila Pioneer Dies at the Age of 87|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20120321006740/en/Don-Julio-Gonz\u00e1lez-Estrada-Tequila-Pioneer-Dies#.UwZSGihBCfS|accessdate=20 February 2014|newspaper=Business Wire|date=21 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Process==\n\nThe agave for Don Julio's Tequila is grown in the highland area of Atotonilco on the family estate. Tequila's major aging process over time takes place in conjunction with the development of agave plants, given that they take seven years to reach maturity. Every agave plant is harvested by hand. The agave plant is cut from its roots and then the spearlike leaves are sheered off. The core that is left is called a pi\u00f1a, which is the raw material used for the making of tequila. The pi\u00f1as are transported on a truck to Don Julio's Distillery where they are cut into equal sized pieces so that they bake evenly. The pi\u00f1as are loaded into brick ovens where they are slowly baked over the course of several days. Then the baked pi\u00f1as are crushed and doused with water, which releases the sweet agave syrup called agave juice. Then yeast is added to the agave water and is left to ferment. After the fermentation process is complete it results in a sweet, slight alcoholic agave beer which is then put into stills where it is distilled to become tequila. At last it is put into stainless steel tanks before bottling, or ex-bourbon casks for aging.<ref name=\"Tequila making\">{{cite web|last=Kleinman|first=Geoff|title=How Tequila is Made: Behind the Scenes of Don Julio Tequila|url=http://www.drinkspirits.com/tequila/tequila-made-scenes-don-julio-tequila/|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Varieties==\n\n* Don Julio Blanco (available also in the US)\n* Don Julio Reposado (available also in the US)<ref>[http://www.tequilasource.com/donjuliotequila.htm ''Don Julio Tequila: Made in the same way since 1942 .''] Retrieved November 27, 2009.</ref>\n* Don Julio A\u00f1ejo (available also in the US)\n* Don Julio 70 A\u00f1ejo Claro (available also in the US)\n* Don Julio 1942 A\u00f1ejo (available also in the US)\n* Don Julio Real Extra A\u00f1ejo (available also in the US)\n\nSeveral of these offerings have performed well at international [[spirit ratings]] competitions.  For example, Don Julio's Real tequila was awarded double gold medals at the 2008 and 2011 San Francisco World Spirits Competition and a silver medal at the 2012 competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.proof66.com/tequila/don-julio-real-tequila.html|title=Proof66.com Ratings Summary for Don Julio Real|publisher= |date= |accessdate=2012-10-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.donjulio.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Diageo plc}}\n\n[[Category:Tequila]]\n[[Category:Diageo brands]]\n[[Category:Alcoholic drink brands]]\n[[Category:Mexican brands]]\n", "name_user": "38.65.36.185", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Julio"}
